### Mobile First Approach

**Mobile-first** means designing for small screens first, then enhancing for larger screens.

---

### The Principle

1. Start with **smallest screen** base styles
2. Add **min-width media queries** to enhance for larger screens
3. Every device gets the base experience
4. Larger devices get progressively more layout

---

### Mobile-First vs Desktop-First

```css
/* Mobile-first: uses min-width */
.column { width: 100%; }  /* Mobile default */

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .column { width: 50%; }  /* Tablet */
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .column { width: 33.33%; }  /* Desktop */
}

/* Desktop-first: uses max-width */
.column { width: 33.33%; }  /* Desktop default */

@media (max-width: 1023px) {
  .column { width: 50%; }  /* Tablet */
}

@media (max-width: 767px) {
  .column { width: 100%; }  /* Mobile */
}
```

---

### Why Mobile-First?

| Benefit | Reason |
|---------|--------|
| Performance | Mobile gets less CSS to parse |
| Simpler | Base styles are simpler |
| Future-proof | New large sizes work automatically |
| SEO | Google prioritizes mobile |
| Accessibility | Forces good defaults |

---

### Mobile-First Example

```css
/* BASE: Mobile (all screens) */
body {
  font-size: 16px;
  line-height: 1.6;
}

.nav {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;  /* Stack on mobile */
}

/* TABLET: 768px+ */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .nav {
    flex-direction: row;
    justify-content: space-between;
  }

  .container {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
}

/* DESKTOP: 1024px+ */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    max-width: 960px;
  }

  .content {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
  }
}

/* LARGE: 1280px+ */
@media (min-width: 1280px) {
  .container {
    max-width: 1200px;
  }
}
```

---

### Viewport Meta Tag

```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```

Required for proper mobile rendering.

---

### Testing Mobile-First

1. Start with narrow viewport (320px)
2. Gradually widen to see enhancements
3. Each breakpoint should add, not override

> **Best Practice:** Always write base styles for mobile first, then add `min-width` queries. Your CSS will be cleaner and more maintainable.
